	(334, 1, '2015-03-06 09:17:15', '2015-03-06 09:17:15', ' <body id="other" class="page page-id-33 page-child parent-pageid-13 page-template page-template-page-about-the-initiative-php win8.1 chrome chrome-0">\r\n\r\n<section class="intro-image" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/cki-template11-headers-aboutinit.jpg&#39;);">\r\n                <header>\r\n                    <h1>Quality of Life Measures?</h1>\r\n                    <hr>\r\n                </header>\r\n            </section>\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>The Concepts of WellBeing and Quality of Life</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                            <p style="margin-top:200px;"><span style="color:green; font-style:italic;">“For the purposes of this website wellbeing and quality of life are used interchangeably.”</span></p>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>Though the concepts have gone by other names and held different definitions, wellbeing and quality of life has been a leading focus of scholarly, philosophical, and religious thought for much of human history. The great philosophers believed that wellbeing meant virtuous living. With the Enlightenment, the notion took hold that absolute happiness could be achieved through proactive human intervention in society’s institutional structures—that it was possible, in effect, to create a heaven on earth, as exemplified by the French revolutions and the various social experiments that followed.</p>\r\n                            <p>With the rise of this notion, societal goals that had previously belonged to the informal realm of civil society—economic development, advancement of human functionings and capabilities, human freedom and creativity, environmental sustainability, fairness, and social justice—now became core political and governmental objectives. Although the foregoing are important considerations of the good society, people of different philosophical, religious, cultural, and political persuasions disagree as to their relative importance for quality of life.</p>\r\n                            <p>The Baugh Center at Baylor University is launching this new, empirically based project because accurate measurements are indispensable for making recommendations and decisions about how best to pursue and achieve a society with a high quality of life. When defined carefully, quality of life and wellbeing are holistic concepts that can be measured relatively precisely and in objective, cross-cultural terms.</p>\r\n                            <p>Together with much of the academic profession in the wellbeing field, The Baugh Center considers wellbeing as consisting a combination of two underlying components. The first is the more short-term and pleasant emotions and feelings of joy that a person experiences at any given time, and the second is a person’s cognitive, evaluative, reflection of his or her life as a whole. The former is more closely aligned with what people today refers to as happiness and the latter is what scholars refers to as life satisfaction.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2 id="about_the_project">About the Project</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>What is wellbeing?</p>\r\n                            <p>Throughout human history, philosophers, poets, theologians, and scholars have sought the answer to that seemingly simple question. From King Solomon to the city squares of ancient Greece to the worldwide conversations of the Internet age, humanity has discussed and debated just what the good life means—and how to help more people achieve it.</p>\r\n                            <p>The Baugh Center seeks to further this conversation as it continues into the 21st century. Through research, education, and discussion, we aim to advance understanding of how individual quality of life intersects with society as a whole, how to comprehend and measure the various aspects of wellbeing and quality of life, and how to inspire people to improve lives in their communities and society at large.</p>\r\n                            <p>As part of this goal, we have produced measures of quality of life for all 50 U.S. states and more than 140 countries. These measures open new doors for research and form the core of our efforts to improve quality of life. The measures focus on six societal dimensions of human wellbeing Opportunity, Health & Environment, Freedom, Community & Relationships, Living Standard, and Peace & Security.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n            </div>', 'About the Project', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '199-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-03-06 09:17:15', '2015-03-06 09:17:15', '', 199, 'http://localhost/life-measures-wordpress/199-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
